Democracy shows how the majority of ordinary Danish citizens provided a solid wall of support for the rights of their country's growing Muslim minority, drawing a sharp distinction between Muslim immigrants and Islamic fundamentalists and supporting the civil rights of Muslim immigrants as fully as those of fellow Danes-for example, Christian fundamentalists. Building on randomized experiments conducted as part of large, nationally representative opinion surveys, Paradoxes of Liberal Democracy also demonstrates how the moral covenant underpinning the welfare state simultaneously promotes equal treatment for some Muslim immigrants and opens the door to discrimination against others.Revealing the strength of Denmark's commitment to democratic values, Paradoxes of Liberal Democracy underlines the challenges of inclusion but offers hope to those seeking to reconcile the secular values of liberal democracy and the religious faith of Muslim immigrants in Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCaricatures and cartoonsxPolitical aspectszDenmark. 0aDemocracyxSocial aspectszDenmark. 0aFreedom of speechzDenmark. 0aIslam and statezDenmark. 0aReligious pluralismxPolitical aspectszDenmark. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Censorship.2bisacsh  aDanish Muslims.  aDanish newspapers.  aDenmark.  aIslam.  aIslamic fundamentalists.  aJyllands-Posten.  aMohammed.  aMuslim immigrants.  aMuslims.  aanti-immigrants.  aanti-immigration.  acartoons.  acategorization paradox.  acentrists.  acivil rights.  acovenant paradox.  ademocratic citizenship.  adiscrimination.  aequal treatment.  aevaluative judgments.  afreedom of expression.  agroup categorization.  aimmigrant minorities.  aimmigrants.  ainclusive tolerance.  aliberal democracy.  aparty systems.  apolitical center.  apoli